  "response_text": "The population of non-learning households (E-RO strategy) initiates at 20 households and undergoes a characteristic three-phase trajectory over the 100-year simulation horizon. During the initial establishment phase (approximately years 0-8), the count exhibits a modest but statistically significant increasing trend, reaching a maximum value of approximately 21.1 households around year 8. This represents a temporary expansion of roughly 5% above the initial allocation.\n\nFollowing this early peak, the system enters an extended decline phase spanning approximately years 8 through 92. Over this 84-year period, the count of E-RO households decreases steadily from the peak of 21.1 to a minimum value of 14.67 households observed near year 92. This decline represents a net reduction of approximately 26% from the initial population, translating to the loss of roughly 5-6 non-learning households over the century. The trajectory is marked by change points around years 20 and 45, which demarcate shifts in the rate of decline. Rolling trend analysis confirms statistically significant decreasing trends throughout the middle period, particularly pronounced between years 11-21 where the rate of decline reaches approximately 0.22 households per year.\n\nIn the final stabilization phase (years 92-100), the trajectory flattens considerably, maintaining values between approximately 14.7 and 15.3 households with no statistically significant directional trend detected. The series concludes at approximately 14.7 households by year 100. Across the full temporal extent, the mean count of non-learning households averages 16.4, with a median value of 15.3, indicating a left-skewed distribution where values cluster in the 14-17 range for the majority of the simulation.\n\nThe oscillation analysis reveals a dominant periodicity of approximately 49 years underlying these trends, suggesting cyclical variations in household persistence superimposed on the long-term declining trajectory. In the context of the grazing system, this pattern indicates that households employing non-learning rule-of-thumb strategies experience progressive attrition over time, likely due to inability to adapt to fluctuating pasture conditions and neighbor behaviors, resulting in higher exit rates compared to learning-enabled counterparts. By the conclusion of the simulation, approximately 73-74% of the original non-learning households remain in the system, having stabilized at this reduced equilibrium state."
}

